# Load required packages and data
library(tidyverse)
library(pander)
dat <- readRDS("10000sims_lmer_naive_10sub_10clust_2arm_sb2pt01_se2-1.rds")

pval_b1_model <- unlist(dat[1,])
est_sb2 <- unlist(dat[2,]) # let's assume anything less than 1e-6 is the weird ones
tiny_est <- est_sb2 < 1e-6
resid_var_model <- unlist(dat[3,])
# [4,] is the NLME model
MSB <- unlist(dat[5,])
MSE <- unlist(dat[6,])
clustvar0 <- unlist(dat[7,])
clustvar1 <- unlist(dat[8,])
ftest_pval <- unlist(dat[9,])
# 10 is equal var t-test
# 11 is uneq var t-test
# 12 is the table of cluster means
pval_tt_eq_var <- unlist(dat[13,])
pval_tt_uneq_var <- unlist(dat[14,])
df_tt_uneq_var <- unlist(dat[15,])
# 16 is the actual data
beta0 <- unlist(dat[17,])
beta0_se <- unlist(dat[18,])
beta1 <- unlist(dat[19,])
beta1_se <- unlist(dat[20,])
SSE <- unlist(dat[21,])
SSB <- unlist(dat[22,])
SSR <- unlist(dat[23,])
sig2_b_dot <- unlist(dat[24,])
sig2_b_dot_neg <- unlist(dat[25,])
sig2_hat <- unlist(dat[26,])
sig2_hat_0 <- unlist(dat[27,])
icc <- MSB / (MSB + MSE)
plotdat <- cbind.data.frame(tiny_est, pval_b1_model, est_sb2, resid_var_model, #modelNLME,
                            MSB, MSE,
                            clustvar0, clustvar1, ftest_pval,# ttest_eq_var, ttest_uneq_var,
                            #clustmeans,
                            pval_tt_eq_var, pval_tt_uneq_var, df_tt_uneq_var,
                            beta0, beta0_se, beta1, beta1_se,
                            SSE, SSB, SSR,
                            sig2_b_dot, sig2_b_dot_neg, sig2_hat, sig2_hat_0, icc)#, test)

Heres the problem:

ggplot(data = plotdat) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = pval_tt_uneq_var), color = "black", fill = "grey") +
  facet_grid(rows = vars(tiny_est), labeller = label_both) +
  xlab("p-value for welch t-test, allows unequal variances (results the same with eq vars)") +
  labs(title = "Small p-values on a t-test correlated with tiny estimates; makes sense, more power")

ggplot(data = plotdat) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = pval_b1_model), color = "black", fill = "grey") +

  xlab("p-value from model") +
  labs(title = "Model p-values are 'missing' low p-values, all in cases of tiny estimates")

sum(pval_tt_uneq_var < .05) / length(pval_tt_uneq_var)
## [1] 0.0445
sum(pval_b1_model < .05) / length(pval_b1_model)
## [1] 0.0377

The difference in TIE rates is being driven by the cases with tiny estimates

Lets find some cases here

lostindx <- as.numeric(rownames(lostcases))
plotdat$lost <- FALSE
plotdat$lost[lostindx] <- TRUE

ggplot(data = plotdat[plotdat$tiny_est==T,]) +
  geom_point(aes(x = abs(beta1)/beta1_se, y = MSB/MSE, color = lost), stroke = 0, alpha = .5) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = 1.96)) +

  labs(title = "A certain beta1 t-value and a certain ratio? (1.96?? not qt with 18 df)")

Looking at the lost data sets in more detail vs.tiny estimates that werent lost

tiny_and_lost_datasets <- dat[16,lostindx] # 149 of them
tiny_but_not_lost_indx <- tiny_est==T & plotdat$lost==F # 4161 of them, we'll probably just use the first 149
tiny_but_not_lost_datasets <- dat[16, tiny_but_not_lost_indx]
outliers_lost <- vector()
outliers_not_lost <- vector()
for(i in 1:length(lostindx)){
  outliers_lost[i] <- max(abs(tiny_and_lost_datasets[[i]]$linpred))
  outliers_not_lost[i] <- max(abs(tiny_but_not_lost_datasets[[i]]$linpred))
}
outlier_dat <- cbind.data.frame(outliers_lost, outliers_not_lost)

ggplot(outlier_dat %>% gather(key = "type", value = "max_outlier")) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = max_outlier), color = "black", fill = "grey") +
  facet_grid(rows = vars(type), labeller = label_both) +
  labs(title = "No big difference in outliers")
